column17: This cult favorite solid balm removes the kind of stubborn makeup that tends to trail behind. As you spread it over your face, it melts into a cleansing oil to spread easily and break down makeup. It doesn’t contain any irritants so most people will have no issue rubbing it gently all over their eyes and lash lines to break down even the most tenacious eye makeup! As a bonus, this method is gentler on your eyes and causes less skin dragging/irritation and lash pulling/fallout than using a cotton pad since your fingers slip around with no friction in the oil. The cherry on top of all of this is that usually with oil cleansers you have to wipe it off with a cloth to remove all the oil from your face. However, this balm includes surfactants that mean it rinses right off when you add water, removing almost all of the makeup/residue from your face and leaving the it ready for a more targeted skin cleanse! It is perfect for most skin types, but especially dry and sensitive types will benefit from this more gentle form of cleansing.

column17: since you have eczema which means you are prone to having a breached epidermal barrier, we recommend steering clear of harsh cleansers. a common ingredient in many cleansers is sodium lauryl sulfate or sodium laureth sulfate (SLS/SLES). this is the ingredient that causes your soaps to foam and bubble. while they may make you feel nice and clean, they can be stripping to more easily irritated skin types. because of this, our first recommendation is the sunday riley ceramic slip cleanser -- this formula substitutes SLS/SLES with a much milder surfactant (aka cleansing agent) called DLS. it'll be much kinder to your skin and effective remove excess sebum and dirt buildup without stripping or irritating your skin.

column17: our first recommendation is the murad 1.5% salicylic cleanser. this formula is gel-based making it optimal for more acne-prone skin types. also, many cleansers are formulated with strong detergents such as sodium lauryl/laureth sulfates (SLS/SLES) which are the ingredients that cause your soaps to foam and bubble. while they may leave your skin feeling nice and clean, they can act as stripping agents! the murad cleanser substitutes SLS/SLES with coco-betaine, a much milder surfactant that is kinder to your skin and won't wreak havoc on your natural oil levels. this cleanser is great for those who want a deep cleanse with some routine routine gentle exfoliation and blackhead prevention!

column17: you also noted that you have some blackheads which is why we're also recommending the paula's choice 2% BHA liquid exfoliant. it's a gentle, non-drying formulation that works in deeper dermal layers. BHAs (beta hydroxy acids/salicylic acid) are lipid-soluble, meaning they can penetrate pores and dissolve the excess sebum and dead skin cells trapped inside. //////// our next recommendation is the paula's choice 2% BHA liquid exfoliant. we chose this formula for you because you noted that you experience some redness -- this is one of the gentler but still effective BHAs on the market. this toner is alcohol-free which is relevant because drying alcohols (look out for ethanol/isopropyl alcohols or alcohol denat) can sometimes worsen symptoms related to acne. these two BHA products will work together nicely to keep blackheads at bay and reduce the severity of breakouts! however, please do note that BHAs can increase photosensitivity, so wearing an SPF is highly recommended (not to mention, a great way to prevent irreversible skin damage)!

column17: we recommend the herbivore blue tansy AHA + BHA mask. AHAs and BHAs (alpha and beta hydroxy acids) work on the skin surface and in deeper dermal layers. AHAs work by essentially undoing the glue holding your dead skin cells together, promoting cell turnover and exfoliation. BHAs penetrate your pores to dissolve the excess sebum and dead skin cells trapped inside. together, they'll work together nicely to brighten, clear up, and fade pigmentation over time. blue tansy is well known for its anti-inflammatory properties, so this mask doubles as a soothing treatment! please do note that AHAs and BHAs can increase photosensitivity, so wearing an SPF that you love daily is highly recommended (not to mention the best way to prevent irreversible skin damage)!
